[1] South Korea: 1 new case, 2 new deaths - MOH 26 Jun 2015
Date: Fri 26 Jun 2015
Source: South Korean MOH [in Korean, trans. by interns at the JW LEE Center for Global Medicine, Seoul National University College of Medicine, Republic of Korea, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323764


MERS-CoV Daily Update
-Total number of cases now stands at 181: 69 currently receiving treatment (38.1 percent), 81 recovered (44.8 percent), and 31 dead (17.1 percent).
- 1 new case, 8 no longer undergoing treatment, 7 recoveries, and 2 additional fatalities compared to previous day's numbers.
- Of the 69 receiving treatment: 56 in stable condition (81.2 percent), 13 reportedly unstable (18.8 percent).
- 82 have contracted the virus nosocomially, 64 have come in contact in-facility while visiting family, and 35 are hospital personnel.

Overview of Confirmed Cases
- The Ministry of Health and Welfare's MERS-CoV Task Force has announced -- as of 6 AM KST, 26 Jun 2015 -- that the number of total patients currently undergoing treatment has decreased by 8 since yesterday bringing the total down to 69 (38.1 percent); 7 have made recoveries, bringing the number up to 81 (44.8 percent).
- The fatality count has risen by 2 and currently stands at 31 (17.1 percent); one new confirmed case.
- Of those current undergoing treatment 56 are in stable condition while 13 are reportedly unstable.

New Recoveries
- A total of 7 patients have made recoveries from 24-25 Jun 2015, boosting the total to 81.
- The newly discharged patients are: patients no. 85 (66 year old female), 106 (60 year old female), 143 (31 year old male), 145 (37 year old male), 155 (42 year old female), 160 (31 year old male), and 161 (79 year old female).
- Dischargees underwent various courses of symptomatic treatments, such as antibiotic and anti-viral treatment. The patients were cleared for discharge after signs of respiratory distress and fever subsided, and confirmatory tests resulted negative.
- Of the 81 total recoveries, 43 (53.1 percent) are male with 38 (46.9 percent) being female; 20 have been in the 40s (24.7 percent), 19 have been in the 50s (23.5 percent), 14 have been in the 30s (17.3 percent), 12 have been in the 60s (14.8 percent), with 10 having been in the 70s (12.3 percent).

New Cases
- 1 new case has been confirmed since yesterday [25 Jun 2015].
- Patient no. 181 (26 year old male, 26) was assigned as patient no. 135's physician during the patient's hospitalization at Seoul Samsung Medical Center on 11-15 Jun 2015. Patient no. 181 started exhibiting symptoms while under home isolation on 17 Jun 2015.

New Fatalities
- Patients no. 87 (79 year old female, diabetes/infarction) and 140 (80 year old female, stage 3 bladder cancer) were pronounced dead between 25 Jun 2015 and the morning of 26 Jun 2015, bringing the fatality count up to 31.
- Of the 31 reported fatalities to date, 21 have been male (67.7 percent), while 10 have been female (32.3 percent); in terms of age distribution, the lion's share of the fatalities have been in the 60s and 70s, with 10 (32.3 percent) fatalities each, followed by 6 (19.4 percent) fatalities in the 80s, 4 (12.9 percent) in the 50s, and 1 (3.2 percent) in the 40s.
- 29 of the 31 fatalities (92 percent) were elderly, immunocompromised, and/or suffering from pre-existing conditions such as COPD [chronic obstructive pulmonary disease], cancer, cerebrovascular disease, and diabetes.

Modes of Transmission and Demographic Characteristics
- A categorical analysis on the modes of transmission of the 181 total cases (minus one currently unaccounted) reveals:
- Nosocomial infection is the most common mode of transmission at 45.3 percent (82 cases), infections as a result of hospital visits by family members comprise 35.4 percent of total cases (64), while infections of faculty and other medical personnel is report to be at 19.3 percent (35)

- Male infectees comprise 61.3 percent of the total cases (111), and females, 38.7 percent (70)
- Total distribution by age of all cases is as follows: 41 patients (22.7 percent) are in the 50s, 36 (19.9 percent) are in their 60s, 30 are in their 70s (16.6 percent), 29 are in their 40s (16 percent), while 26 are in their 30s (14.4 percent).

Isolations and Quarantine
- As of 26 Jun 2015 6 AM KST, 2931 are under quarantine with the reflected numbers being 10.9 percent higher than previous day's numbers (an increase of 289); the total number of those released from quarantine has increased to 12 203, which equates to an increase of 267 compared to previous day's numbers.
- Of the 2931 under quarantine, 2172 are under home isolation (a 15.7 percent increase, or an increase of 294), while the number of hospital quarantines has also increased by 5 (0.7 percent), bringing the total number of hospital quarantines to 759.

