[Again, an impressive set of analyses on the ongoing (and hopefully winding down) outbreak in South Korea. Our collective thanks to the South Koreans and Eurosurveillance for making this available to us so rapidly. It is interesting to see the comparison between the South Korean outbreak and the SARS outbreak from 2002-2003 -- suggesting (not surprisingly) that these 2 different coronaviruses seem to be behaving in very similar epidemiologic patterns, with the superspreading events being key events for rapid outbreaks.

I highly recommend reading the original article at the source URL and looking at the figures and tables. Figure 2 is an impressive representation of the 3 superspreading events, showing how they were responsible for the overwhelming majority of cases reported as of the date of these analyses. For a more in-depth statistical analysis of the superspreading events, I highly recommend reading Kucharski AJ, Althaus CL: The role of superspreading in Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) transmission. Euro Surveill. 2015; 20(25): pii=21167; available at http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=21167. The authors mention they found ".....substantial potential for superspreading; even though it is likely that R0 is less than 1 overall, our analysis indicates that cluster sizes of over 150 cases are not unexpected for MERS-CoV infection."

The discussion suggesting the variance in case fatality rates observed in South Korea versus those seen in the Middle East -- "Greater severity in the sporadic cases could be an artifact of surveillance biased towards infections associated with serious illnesses," is something we have mentioned before. - Mod.MPP]

